what if we made a method on ArgSchemaParser of 

```
def get_parser(self):
   return utils.schema_argparser(self.schema)
```

and that way extending ArgSchemaParser would be cleaner.

you could call it a bug, or you could call it a design error, but yes the text_field_embedder section of a config probably should have looked like

```
  "model": {
    "type": "bidaf",
    "text_field_embedder": {
      "token_embedders": {
          "tokens": { ... },
          "token_characters": { ... },
         }
      }
    },
```

instead of

```
  "model": {
    "type": "bidaf",
    "text_field_embedder": {
      "tokens": { ... },
      "token_characters": { ... },
      }
    },
```

but we can't really change it now without breaking all of the model configs

@leecow Two of these are commits from corefx--commits for EF issues are in the EF repo.

The commit for 11993 is: https://github.com/aspnet/EntityFrameworkCore/pull/12000/commits/a4a414432b20ae68ce53e4b981ecf9e718f98731

The commit for 11977 is: https://github.com/aspnet/EntityFrameworkCore/pull/12123/commits/9409a1f25b7603bb8dce747aff2a7df5744f5efe

A bit later to the party, but this one was actually kind of meant to be implicit, so you could have numpy-like constructs and use a string literal every time a dtype is required (and it's only required in `array` methods/ctors).E.g.:

```cpp
py::array(100, "|S4");
py::array({2, 3}, "i");
```
